{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti**, **Yājñavalkya Smṛti**, and **Āṅgirasa Smṛti** open with sages (ṛṣis) approaching a teacher figure (Manu, Yājñavalkya, or Āṅgirasa) and requesting instruction on *dharma* (righteous law), after which the teacher expounds doctrinal content.[^1][^2][^3]\n\nNo other works in the corpus contain explicit teacher-student dialogues of this doctrinal nature. Nāradasmṛti, for instance, begins as a legal exposition without such framing, and the remaining texts (poems, political treatises, etc.) are narrative, poetic, or expository without structured instruction.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 1, [translation/](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-879544).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 1, [translation/](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-97f0a4).\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, Chapter 1, [translation/](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-d38615).\n[^4]: Nāradasmṛti, Chapter 1, [translation/](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/unknown-naradasmrti-7650d2/01/translation/#p-287f20).",
